{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c053127e-18cb-43cc-b727-ba6bef4d9817","content":"For a .NET Web API, use the `webapi` template:\n\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi\n```\n\n**Authentication options** (`--auth`):\n\n| Option | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `None` | No auth (default) |\n| `IndividualB2C` | Azure AD B2C |\n| `SingleOrg` | Single-tenant Azure AD |\n| `MultiOrg` | Multi-tenant Azure AD |\n| `Windows` | Windows/Negotiate auth |\n\n**Example with auth:**\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --domain myorg.onmicrosoft.com\n```\n\nYou can also add JWT Bearer or API key auth manually via `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer`. Run `dotnet new webapi --help` for all options.\n\nWant me to scaffold a project with a specific auth configuration?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6aefd51e-e79b-41e5-adb7-ee40441d2093","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":292,"requestId":"A80E:11F9F2:C74657:E1F83F:6A02797F"},"id":"ced0b83f-aee3-4208-a293-a6cff78fd080","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:51:19.141Z","parentId":"b76dd868-0b1f-4788-b396-7947def58a14"}
